title: Matcha Wreath Babka
text:
Matcha babka wreath for my Christmas brunch.


This Christmas, I decided to depart from the traditional rich chocolate babka and experiment with something more vibrant. Inspired by Sherryâ€™s Chocolate Babka, this version swaps out cocoa for matcha, resulting in a beautifully braided wreath with a striking green interior and a sophisticated, earthy sweetness.


Time
4 hours



Ingredients

The Brioche Dough

75g Whole Eggs (save the leftover egg for egg wash)
18g Egg Yolk
81g Cold Milk

81g Cold Water
193g Bread Flour

193g All-Purpose Flour
6g Salt
11g Milk Powder

51g Sugar

1g Matcha power

6g Instant Yeast
77g Unsalted Butter (soften)



Matcha Filling

39g Unsalted Butter

95g White Chocolate
33g Sugar
13g Matcha Powder





Instructions

In a standmixer bowl with dough attachment, add in whole eggs, egg yolk, milk, water, bread flour, all purpose flour, salt, milk powder, sugar and matcha power. Mix on low speed (speed 2) until dough forms.
Add in instant yeast. Mix until combined.
Chill dough in fridge for 20 minutes.
Mix on medium speed (speed 4) for ~5 minutes; look for stretchy dough but not window pane yet.
Add in soften butter, mix on low speed (speed 2) until butter is incorporated. Then mix on medium speed (speed 4) until window pane consistency is reached (~5-10 minutes).
Put dough into a greased bowl; let it proof until doubled in size (~1 hour).
Degas dough and roll out to a 21x15 inch (53x38cm) rectangle.
Spread matcha filling onto the dough evenly.
Roll up the dough into a log, fairly tightly.
Cut log down the middle, and braid to form into a wreath shape.
Proof until double in size (~45-60 minutes). Brush on egg wash before baking.
Preheat the oven to 350Â°F / 180Â°C, bake for 25-30 minutes on the middle to lower rack. After about 10 minutes, when the surface is coloured, cover with foil to prevent the top from being burnt.


Matcha Filling

Add all ingredients into a bowl and melt over a double broiler until paste forms, set aside. Warm it up if paste is too thick and chill in the fridge if the paste is too thin. You want a spreadable consistency.

title: Hotdog Predictor
text:
Can a business name reveal whatâ€™s on the menu? This project explores text-based classification using the City of Vancouverâ€™s Street Food Vending dataset.
I engineered a binary target from vendor descriptions and trained multiple models, including Decision Trees and Logistic Regression, to identify hot dog vendors based solely on their business names. After rigorous cross-validation, a tuned NaÃ¯ve Bayes classifier emerged as the top performer with 79% accuracy. The project highlights the challenges of imbalanced datasets and the nuances of classifying minority target classes in urban data.
